## 1. Dependency Health Posture (5-tier cadence)

**Purpose**: keep the codebase on supported, security-patched dependencies *without* requiring anyone to remember to "run an audit". The system pushes problems at you; you don't pull. This section codifies the 5 layers that together turn dependency hygiene from a manual chore into an enforced posture.

**Origin**: <TICKET-ID> + <TICKET-ID> incident (2026-03-11 → 2026-05-08). The team accumulated 25 stale branches, 197 failed CI runs, 1 critical + 25 high CVEs, and 5 unpatched Next 14.x CVEs because (a) GitHub native security alerts were disabled, (b) CI was not a real gate, and (c) no periodic process surfaced drift. The 5-tier cadence below prevents recurrence.

### Tier 1 — Real-time push (seconds, automated)

**Trigger**: a CVE drops upstream against a dependency in `package-lock.json`.

| Mechanism | Required state | How to verify |
|---|---|---|
| **GitHub Dependabot Alerts** | `vulnerability_alerts: enabled` repo setting | `gh api repos/{owner}/{repo} --jq '.security_and_analysis.dependabot_security_updates'` → `enabled` |
| **Automated Security Updates** | `automated_security_fixes: enabled` repo setting | Same query as above. Auto-opens PR with the fix |
| **Email + Bell notifications** | Repo watcher with "Security alerts" enabled in user settings | Profile → Notifications → ensure security alerts are not muted |

**Apply (one-time, on every repository in EM Ecosystem)**:
```bash
gh api -X PUT repos/{owner}/{repo}/vulnerability-alerts
gh api -X PUT repos/{owner}/{repo}/automated-security-fixes
```

Without these enabled, GitHub's native security infrastructure runs but produces no notifications. This is the single highest-leverage configuration in the entire posture.

### Tier 2 — CI gate (immediate at PR time)

**Trigger**: any PR (human or dependabot) that introduces a new high/critical npm audit finding.

| Mechanism | Required state |
|---|---|
| Branch protection on `main` | required-status-checks includes Layer 2 Dependency Audit (both packages); see Section 2 Required Repository Configuration B |
| Workflow `security.yml` Layer 2 jobs | run on every PR (existing) |
| Workflow `security.yml` Security Gate (final) | required (existing) |

Without branch protection enforcing Layer 2 (planned in <TICKET-ID>), Tier 1 alerts become advisory: someone can ignore them and merge anyway. The gate is what turns "we know" into "we cannot proceed".

### Tier 3 — Weekly safety net (Monday 06:00 UTC, automated)

**Trigger**: scheduled cron job runs `npm audit` against current `main`, opens or updates a tracking issue if any high/critical vuln remains, ages out closed items, alerts on PR staleness.

| Job | File | Behaviour |
|---|---|---|
| Full Dependency Audit | `.github/workflows/weekly-audit.yml` (existing) | runs `npm audit` per package matrix |
| **Dependency Health Issue (NEW)** | extension to `weekly-audit.yml` | opens/updates a single permanent `[dep-health]` issue with the current vuln counts and breakdown |
| Branch Hygiene Audit | `weekly-audit.yml` (added 2026-05-08, the framework release layer branch-hygiene-audit commit) | lists branches merged but not deleted, opens issue if drift detected |
| **Stale Dependabot PR Alerter (NEW)** | extension to `weekly-audit.yml` | opens issue if any dependabot PR open >14 days without activity |

This tier guarantees that "no notifications fired" never means "nothing was wrong" — the cron job confirms zero-state actively.

### Tier 4 — EOL tracker (proactive, 90-day lead time)

**Trigger**: scheduled cron job queries `endoflife.date` API for each critical framework (Node, Next, React, NestJS, Prisma, Tailwind, ESLint, TypeScript). When any framework's currently-installed major version is within 90 days of its declared EOL, the workflow opens a tracking issue with a migration-plan template.

| Job | File | Frequency |
|---|---|---|
| **EOL Tracker (NEW)** | new workflow (or job in `weekly-audit.yml`) | weekly, but issue threshold = 90 days from EOL |

**Why 90 days**: a major migration ticket needs `/plan + /develop + /verify + /commit + /update-docs` cycles, plus testing under realistic load. 90 days lead time is the industry minimum to plan, schedule, and execute without rushed risk.

**Tracked frameworks (initial)**:
- `nodejs` (currently Node 22 — track LTS schedule)
- `next.js` (currently 14.2.x — already 5 CVEs unpatched, 14.x has limited support window)
- `react` (currently 18.3.1 — 19 is current)
- `typescript` (incremental, but 5.7+ is current; 5.4 is behind)
- `tailwindcss` (currently 3.4 — 4.x is current, 3.x supported until further notice)
- `eslint` (currently 8.x — **EOL since 2024-09**; immediate migration ticket)
- `nestjs` (currently 11.x — 12 not yet released)
- `prisma` (currently 7.x — current)

### Tier 5 — Quarterly + annual review (human, scheduled)

**Trigger**: explicit calendar entry; not automated.

| Cadence | Activity | Output |
|---|---|---|
| **Monthly** (1st Monday) | 30-min triage of Tier 3 issues + Tier 4 tickets | If any major bump >6 weeks in the open backlog, schedule a migration ticket |
| **Quarterly** (sprint planning) | Dependency Health Posture + **Audit WARN Register review** (`audit-warn-register.md`) | Decide if a "Migration Sprint" is warranted; re-classify any WARN trending ↑ to Jira ticket; confirm Accepted-Risk items are still acceptable (next: **2026-08-09**) |
| **Annual** | Full security audit per `manual-security-plan.md` + WARN Register full pass | Updated SBOM, license audit, framework retrospective, posture document refresh, WARN backlog re-prioritization |

### Major Bump SLA

The team's policy on how far behind a critical framework can be:

| Framework category | Maximum lag from latest stable | Trigger for migration ticket |
|---|---|---|
| **Critical (Next, NestJS, Prisma, React, Node LTS)** | 1 major version | When upstream releases N+1 stable, plan migration before N reaches EOL |
| **Tooling (TypeScript, ESLint, Tailwind)** | 1 major version | Same |
| **Build (Webpack, Vite, postcss)** | 2 major versions | Lower priority unless blocking |
| **Types (`@types/*`)** | Match runtime engine version | If using Node 22, `@types/node` should be `^22.x` |

A framework being on a fully-EOL major (e.g. ESLint 8 today) is an automatic HIGH-priority migration ticket regardless of the matrix above.

### Roles and notification routing

| Role | Tier 1-2 | Tier 3-4 | Tier 5 |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Repo maintainer** (currently @emillionnetworking-ltd-labs) | email + bell + assigned to auto-issues | reviewer of weekly tracking issue | owner of monthly + quarterly review |
| **AI agent (Claude)** | does NOT auto-resolve security alerts | can be invoked to /plan a migration ticket from an EOL issue | input for posture review, not decision-maker |
| **Auto-merge** | only patch + types in devDeps after CI passes | n/a | n/a |

### Non-goals of this section

- This is NOT a substitute for application-level threat modeling.
- This is NOT a substitute for the audit framework — see `audit-standards.mdc`. Tier 5 annual review FEEDS the audit framework, not replaces it.
- This is NOT a substitute for code review — Tier 2 is technical gate, code review is human gate, both are required.

